The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
The people must go in the centers of Service for the Applicants of Visa before their interview in the Consular Section\; the cost the latency will be more reduced.
Starting from January 10th, 2011 the procedure of treatment of the visas to the Embassy and consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of the applicants will have to present itself to the centers of Service for the Applicants of Visa (ASC, according to its English initials) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The staff of ASC will take the biometric information of the applicant, who will be revised by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the candidates, among whom one mentions the following ones:
The total costs to treat the visa will be lower, it will not be more necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the treatment of the visa and another so that the service of mail delivers the document.
The candidate will carry out a single payment which will cover the three services.
The current tariff will remain the same one: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a visa of tourist, 150 dollars in the case of visas with request (Ci-includes the visas for temporary works) and 390 dollars for the visas of tradesmen and investors.
The people who wish to renew their visa will not have to present themselves to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will be presented only to the closer ASC where they will present the documents and their prints will be taken.
Because of fact that biometric information will be taken in the ASC, the applicants which wishes a second go to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there less time than before.
In the same way, the applicants of visa to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will not pay any more the extra tariff of service of 26 dollars.
For other information on the new procedure to request the visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
