Climate: how France fiddles with its promises of financings
One year after the Agreement of Copenhagen, it is time to examine the respect of the promises of financings quickly resolved (known as financings fast start or early) carried out by the developed countries.
And the large French messing around is revealed.
In the agreement of Copenhagen, the developed countries were committed providing 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (either 420 million a year).
At the time of the opening of the COP16, the EU left the big game to persuade its partners of reality of his commitment concerning the financings fast start: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side vent, distribution of booklets...
The operation transparency appreciable and is appreciated with its right value: the developing countries and the civil society would like that all the developed countries make in the same way with the same level of precision.
The EU announces to have released in 2010 2.2 billion euros, which puts it on the good way for the respect of its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when one looks in detail, the things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the agreement of Copenhagen, "new and additional," in order to ensure that an extra effort is carried out without being to the detriment of the government Aid with the development.
Unfortunately, there does not exist agreement on what means "new and additional."
Whereas the European Commission had proposed a harmonization, certain States members whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, each one chooses the reference which is appropriate to him best.
The European Commission for example regarded as reference the year 2009: the international financings are maintained, and she adds 150 million to it over three years under the financings fast start.
Other countries chose similar references in terms of year or terms of level of government aid to the development.
On the other hand, France estimates that the financings of "all the new projects" of year 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of the previous years or the total level of government Aid to the development.
Concretely, the full amount of the support of France for the developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), she claims to respect her commitment as regards "new and additional" financings...
Another crucial factor, the distribution between gifts and loans.
There still, there does not exist rule and each one chooses its way of calculating.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ lent is equivalent to 1€ given.
Obviously, that is not easily justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If use of loans can to be justified for certain investments which are profitable (often projects related to the attenuation of the emissions which rests on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present one euro which one will recover as equivalent with one euro that one gives... At most, should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the country lender (either the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has to only make of such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% from loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - to see the document of the EU to check by yourself.
It is the only Convention country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires there to 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) respect their commitments with 100% of gifts.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts 1€ to satisfy her commitment, France puts only 10 centimes and considers that the effort is comparable.
Pretty conjuring trick!
In short, in its financing fast start, France operates a double swindle: on the one hand on the evolution of the action in time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
While spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make believe that it spends about it 420 "new and additional" million in coherence with its promises.
The handling of the Finance Minister (because it seems well that it is Bercy which carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why the other States members would continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely easily deceived...
The chapter of the early financings is only one small question, of relative short-term, compared to the whole of the discussions about the climate.
But it could be a grain of sand moreover in the immense machine which is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that will not be the case.
At all events, it is essential to learn the lessons from this first year of early financings.
First of all, France could announce a change in its mode of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect of its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But especially, France could advance the discussions on the challenges of long-term financings (another crucial chapter currently discussed): one will not escape the question from "the additionality" or the mode from accounting from the loans.
France could change its position to become as progressist on these challenges as it is it on the different one.
